You had me at hello at this slide - Shopper DNA personalization slide.

Also - what if you intuit that she likes red, just her ability to go back and change. Making implicit more explicit - to say no that's not correct

And I think what I was thinking about was we don't necessarily want to have CogScale or anyone else rune very experience on the website, for product recommendations everything else- so what is the ability for them in a smart more real-time way be the place where the data is collected, and serve as the customer preferences component. As long as they could get the data from the other things

3 main things we're trying to achieve with preferences

  • All these experiences are gathering data in their own way. Very frustrating for customers because we are asking for data but it isn't powering experiences in the other ways. Standardized hub and provide a means of retrieving it consistently for everybody
  • Then revamping a hub where someone can explicitly update their preferences 
  • Use some of that transformation of getting people to save more things as explicit preferences. Looking to do more experimentation, when you check out, you just bought these three things and we have that data more centralized we can be personalizing throughout. So that was certainly some of the vision, it sounds like you guys could help us. I know we didn't look into a vendor at one point to see if they could when we looked at this other particular vendor we didn't think they could really hep us because we should need to do some of our own api work anyway, and they had at toolkit that could maybe build a hub UI, but we figured we'd build that anyway. So there wasn't good value there for us. It sounds like you guys would be in a better position because there is this opportunity to collate a bunch of different dat sources and do the crunching to provide that. 

The problem with our exhaust is that it's incredibly noisy, you have v day , christmas, wedding and any other random birthday are you shopping for you or another person. something like 75% of people who buy mens clothing are women. 

How do we get them to participate more- her own preferences but asking about those she shops for so like a profile within a profile so like someone else she wants to save as she's shopping for other people. 

What are you reliant on to get that clickstream data? Daniel - we have an API you can send signals to to capture that data

That is something we want to experiment with- trying different ways to prompt her and what is the right point in her journey

Question - around the signal, there would be business rules around prioritizing the signal. Do you offer that? A like versus a pin - (Matt says you can set the initial weights but you want the system to figure some of that out on its own) So you could take that one step further and say time looking at a particular thumbnail, even if they still swipe whichever way as no, could be a signal as well. I"m just worried because by occasion it could be different, when you try to do a one size fits all it has never historically worked for that. How do you get your weight for her versus her versus her...

Essentially you can set various parameters and its beneficial in the beginning or with new people, but ultimately it is learning. You don't have to set a bunch of parameters across everything

The other problem we have is using core metrics, and it doesn't tie sessions across devices. I might be at home on my desktop and its still me on my - our interactions are so low even for our top customers, not daily. We haven't been terribly successful on an ongoing basis enriching a profile. Authenticated and anonymous. 

At the end of the day if we have a bunch of cookie IDs, how does a third party link the at the end of the day if you can't give them any more information than a cookie ID. I think what we could do is give you a read by device by cookie or known profile customers and say this is the frequency from what we can tell- there is a way we can piece it together but we will not get to that in the next year or so, but what is the best channel to plug us into initially. 

You're right, our customers don't come back that often, but obviously if they sign in, they are explicit users they come back more often and manage their profile- great. If they don't, this is really where the concern of customer preferences is- you want to learn what they're doing. The in session building of a profile is hugely advantageous for us. 

Let's talk about the unknown customer- how do you create a ProfileOfOne on the fly. We could probably figure out the known, the more lucrative is the unknown. So everyone playing Swipe & Shop has a profile. At the end of the day, if I do come back more frequently, then you have a more personal relevant experience, the ID will stay the same. Just the fact that you can create that. 

A good takeaway would be for your to map out the data flow between an anonymous and known customer. The unknown is the one I don't think you'll be able to lift enough data to influence that customer's session in real-time. 

Our top shoppers shop monthly, the average is 1-2 times a year. 

What I really want to make sure we focus on is the profile component. Can we actually get that data, if someone is interacting with product recommendations and CogScale is not doing product recommendations, is that valuable to you provided we can get them to you and feed into her profile. 

As long as we can give you that information, this is a much bigger ecosystem conversation. Could this be the solution for customer preferences in the short term?

A concern is what is the performance overhead of sending you guys the signal information and querying back to her profile data. 

Swipe & Shop is like 2% of people who actually use it. We do client side and server side to scale, so multiple  as long as your performance is down to hundreds of milliseconds we should be fine, but we find vendors who commit to that and fall on their faces

Liz - what I would like is to figure out if this actually could be a solution for us from a customer preferences standpoint. You may  need to have a technical conversation, does this solve our problem, to see if we can or should proceed this way. 

Do you have any abstracts- what would be the steps to maturity - if there is a roadmap and path to maturity, we would like to talk to those customers about how that journey unfolded. Is any of those a parallel to draw to maturity- in terms of building up from where they are right now. Healthcare is more regulated than retail. 

Is it going to be able to solve our problem in a much better way than we could solve it ourselves?

It’s latest AI investment was on Monday, leading an $11 million Series B for AI cybersecurity startup Protenus. It was the second time KPV participated in a funding round for the company — the previous being a Series A in July 2017, which raised $3 million. Cognosante Ventures, the venture arm of the healthcare information technology company, also participated in two funding rounds. Protenus has raised a total of $19.4 million to date, according to Crunchbase.

Officially, Kaiser Permanente Ventures focuses its investing on information technology, healthcare services, therapeutics, and diagnostics and drug delivery, but AI seems to have become a particular focus. Its investments include Ginger.io, a digital AI mental health provider; Proteus Digital Health, which develops digital medicines that collect and aggregate various behavioral, physiological and therapeutic metrics; and Big Health, an AI-backed behavioral medicine program.
